sed","1228":"1228","1349":"1349","Aft 1325":"after 1325","1248":"1248","1325":"1325","1225":"1225","about 1349":"about 1349","1256":"1256","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1291":"1291","Thorpe, Derbyshire, England":"Thorpe, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Beakby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Skipwith","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Surrey): variant of   Skipworth  .","History: The main Skipwith family held the manor of Skipwith in England in the early Middle Ages, and direct descendants can be traced to the present day. In the 13th century they moved from Yorkshire to Lincolnshire, where their principal seat was at southern Ormsby. In the early 17th century there was further migration, to Leicestershire, Warwickshire, and across the Atlantic to VA. Other bearers of the name seem to have been tenants of Lincolnshire manors held by the Skipworth family, and to have taken the surname of their overlords."],"variants":[{"name":"Skipworth","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): habitational name from Skipwith (East Yorkshire), from Old Northumbrian <i>scīp</i> (Old English <i>scēap</i> ‘sheep’), + Old English <i>wīc</i> ‘dwelling, specialized farm’, later replaced by Old Norse <i>vithr</i> ‘wood’; initial <i>Sk-</i>, instead of <i>Sh-</i>, is also due to Scandinavian influence."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Skipwith was born in 1260, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John de Skipwith, was 36 and his mother, Isabelle Arches, was 33. He had at least 2 sons. He died about 1349, at the age of 90."},"et":{"1260–about 1349":"1260–umbes 1349","1248–1349":"1248–1349","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1256–Male":"1256–Surnud","1260–1349":"1260–1349","1291–1349":"1291–1349","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1225–1325":"1225–1325","1228–Female":"1228–Surnud","1228":"1228","1349":"1349","Aft 1325":"pärast 1325","1248":"1248","1325":"1325","1225":"1225","about 1349":"umbes 1349","1256":"1256","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1291":"1291","Thorpe, Derbyshire, England":"Thorpe, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beakby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1260–about 1349":"1260–noin 1349","1248–1349":"1248–1349","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","1256–Male":"1256–Kuollut","1260–1349":"1260–1349","1291–1349":"1291–1349","1295–Male":"1295–Kuollut","1225–1325":"1225–1325","1228–Female":"1228–Kuollut","1228":"1228","1349":"1349","Aft 1325":"1325 jälkeen","1248":"1248","1325":"1325","1225":"1225","about 1349":"noin 1349","1256":"1256","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1291":"1291","Thorpe, Derbyshire, England":"Thorpe, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Beakby,